{"questionId":"19746","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>A <strong>Gaussian integer</strong> is a complex number, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>z</mi></math>, such that <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>z</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>a</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>b</mi><mtext>i</mtext></math> where <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mi>b</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">ℤ</mi></math>. In this question, you are asked to investigate certain divisibility properties of Gaussian integers.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Consider two Gaussian integers,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>α</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn><mtext>i</mtext></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>β</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mtext>i</mtext></math>, such that&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>γ</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>α</mi><mi>β</mi></math>&nbsp;for some Gaussian integer&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>γ</mi></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Now consider two Gaussian integers,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>α</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn><mtext>i</mtext></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>γ</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>11</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mtext>i</mtext></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The norm of a complex number <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>z</mi></math>, denoted by <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>N</mi><mfenced><mi>z</mi></mfenced></math>, is defined by <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>N</mi><mfenced><mi>z</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><msup><mfenced open=\"|\" close=\"|\"><mi>z</mi></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></math>. For example, if <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>z</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><mtext>i</mtext></math> then <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>N</mi><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><mtext>i</mtext></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><msup><mn>2</mn><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mn>3</mn><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>13</mn></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>A <strong>Gaussian prime</strong> is a Gaussian integer, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>z</mi></math>, that <strong>cannot</strong> be expressed in the form <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>z</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>α</mi><mi>β</mi></math> where <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>α</mi><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mi>β</mi></math> are Gaussian integers with&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>N</mi><mfenced><mi>α</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mi>N</mi><mfenced><mi>β</mi></mfenced><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>1</mn></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>By expressing the positive integer <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>c</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mi>d</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math> as a product of two Gaussian integers each of norm <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>c</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mi>d</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math>, show that <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi></math> is not a Gaussian prime.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>c</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mi>d</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mrow><mi>c</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>d</mi><mtext>i</mtext></mrow></mfenced><mfenced><mrow><mi>c</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>d</mi><mtext>i</mtext></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>N</mi><mfenced><mrow><mi>c</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>d</mi><mtext>i</mtext></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mi>N</mi><mfenced><mrow><mi>c</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>d</mi><mtext>i</mtext></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>c</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mi>d</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>R1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>N</mi><mfenced><mrow><mi>c</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>d</mi><mtext>i</mtext></mrow></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mi>N</mi><mfenced><mrow><mi>c</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>d</mi><mtext>i</mtext></mrow></mfenced><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>1</mn></math>&nbsp;(since <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>c</mi><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mi>d</mi></math> are positive)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>R1</strong></em></p>\n<p>so <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>c</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mi>d</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math> is not a Gaussian prime, by definition&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>AG</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[3 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"19746","referenceCode":"EXN.3.AHL.TZ0.2e","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"By expressing the positive integer n=c2+d2 as a product of two Gaussian integers each of norm c2+d2, show that n is not a Gaussian prime.","paper":"3","level":"HL","questionNumber":"e","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 3]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 1—Number and algebra","Topic 1—Number and algebra","AHL 1.13—Polar and Euler form"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}